reviews.review_text: one of those magical nights This was one of those legendary nights.  1977 was a stong year for the boys..a lot of strong , very electric shows.  All during the fall tour we heard hints of China Cat & hoped it'd be brought back.  Candace told us, between sets, that indeed China Cat had been played that night during the sound check.  At least that's what I remember through the psychedelic haze that seemed to envelope Winterland that nite.  I remember Weir & Garcia leaving the stage while Phil stayed on during  Drums/space.   We hoped they were cooking up something good.   When we heard the first notes of China Cat the place practically exploded.  China-Rider-China Doll was a great moment & helped us to believe that any song could  be brought back at any time.  This show far outshone New Years & the rest of that Winterland run.
a+ quite possibly the best terrapin i've ever heard.

Hello. Do you have NYE runs in a can?
The second of a four day run, of possibly the best NYE shows ever. Featuring the return of China>Rider, this show is almost as good as the landmark next night and the pair are back-to-back top 50 shows (with only two repeated songs). They are also the best shows of late '77 and bear repeated listening. First Set. Busting out t'gate with a buoyant Jack Straw (even if there's a little shoes-in-dryer). Listen closely and there's a Teddy Bear's Picnic before a solid They Love Each Other. Bobby nearly trainwrecks Mama Tried (the show's low mark is also the briefest). Starting with a nicely tempo'd Loser, the rest of the set is celestial. Looks Like Rain has intricate fills from Jer. Bobby is amazing on Tennessee, and Minglewood is a platoon of blur, trying to track Jer as he levitates the building. This is the shit that made him famous with his instrument (btw, he was back to playing Wolf at this run). Granted the tempo gets lost on Sugaree, but the energy coming in is a direct permeation and it blooms in loops of golden static. Don't touch them! Observe only! There's a brief Heart & Soul tuning w/Hoagy Phil's patter, then Promised Land is an energy-burst summation of the set [Keith's solo is unfortunately obscured]. Second Set. Another burst-start with Bertha. The busy drums are a big component of this set. Good Lovin' is the tolling bells for the bacchanalia. The next two are strong in context, and though the verses are a bit messy in Playing, the jam provides interest [the OFF has a 29sec edit @~14:13]. It's an exciting return for China Cat, the first since 10/74, but it's actually a one-off – the next is 2/79. No rust here, and the Rider is unique, unpredictable, with no second solo. Instead there's a fanfare at the end – though accidental, as Jer repeats the chorus and they flow with it (Keith is a deity). China Doll is just the 3rd since '74, yet polished, and has a concentrated end jam before the drummers take over (as well as Keith on harpsichord). Not Fade loses tempo but it's all about the superb middle jam. The Playing reprise has a tempered Bobby & Donna. Terrapin is a heavy version, played exactingly and faved by many [the very beginning is found only on aud_92374; the OFF has a 36sec edit @8:25]. Listen for Keith again during Johnny B. Goode . 1st Set:  A 2nd Set: A- Overall = 5 stars Highlights: Almost the whole show SOURCES: The cousinit_20370 runs way too slow and has low fidelity. Most AUDs run way too fast (aud_92374 & jfishman_108432). The better AUD is 133042_aud, which runs just slightly fast, needing -1% pitch correction. For SBDs, 137198_sbd is a set two upgrade and 141740_sbd_pcm_dalton is the whole show upgrade with tunings and patched, but the 2nd set needs +1% pitch correction. Dick's 10 has most of the show (tunings are cut, levels & balance are a bit wonky, it's missing Roses, Sunrise and parts of Playing and Terrapin).

Dick's Picks 10 Dick cut The Roses and Sunrise, presumably to make room for the best jam sequence of the run (12/30 Estimated->Eyes->St. Stephen->Sugar Magnolia). First China-Rider post-hiatus (last played 10/20/74, 103 shows). Worthwhile listen for that, embedded within a tasty Playin' sandwich. It's also 1977. Check it out.
